Cyberattacks on the business world have become more frequent lately.
Access to data from companies such as JP Morgan, Yahoo, Home Depot and Target has caused them losses in the hundreds of millions, and in some cases even billions of dollars.
It doesn't take too many of these attacks to wreak havoc on the global economy.
The public sector is also not immune from such problems.
From 2012 to 2014, there was a significant data breach at the Office of Human Resource Services.
Access to due diligence and fingerprint data has been disrupted for 22 million employees.
There are known attempts by government-sponsored hackers to influence election results in a number of countries using stolen data.
The last two big data disclosures involve the Bundestag, the German federal parliament, and the theft of emails from the US Democratic National Committee.
The cyber threat affects our democratic processes.
The situation is even getting worse.
As computer technology advances, data protection systems become more vulnerable.
A new type of computer technology is also a matter of concern - computing on quantum computers, which use the microscopic properties of nature to dramatically increase computing power.
It is so powerful that it can break many modern encryption systems.
Is the situation so hopeless?
Maybe it's time to pack our vital data and prepare for the imminent digital apocalypse?
I would say, "It's not time yet."
Quantum computers are still in development and will take many years before they are put into practice.
More importantly, there are major breakthroughs in encryption taking place.
This is a particularly exciting time for me in the history of secure communications.
About 15 years ago, when I learned about the new possibility of creating quantum effects that do not exist in nature, I was very excited.
I was intrigued by the idea of applying fundamental laws of physics to create more secure encryption.
Today, a number of companies and laboratories around the world, including mine, are working on these technologies to put them into practice.
Right.
Now we are preparing to fight the quantum with the quantum.
So how does this all work?
First, let's take a quick excursion into the world of encryption.
For this we need a briefcase, some important documents that we want to send to our friend, James Bond, and a lock to keep everything safe.
Since our information is top secret, we need a special portfolio.
It has a special combination lock: when closed, it converts all text in documents to random numbers.
You put the documents in the briefcase, close the lock - at this very moment, all the documents are converted to random numbers - and send the briefcase to James.
While the briefcase is on the way, you call James to give him the code.
After receiving the briefcase, he enters the code, the documents are decrypted, and voila - you just sent an encrypted message to James Bond.
(Laughter) A funny example, but it illustrates three important elements of coding.
Code - we call it the "encryption key".
It's like a password.
Calling James to tell him the lock combination code.
This is called "key exchange" -
ensuring that you securely get the encryption key from the right place.
And a lock that encodes and decodes the document.
This is called the "coding algorithm".
Using a key, it converts text in documents to random numbers.
A good algorithm will encode in such a way that without the key, the document is very difficult to decrypt.
The importance of encryption is that if someone takes possession of a briefcase and breaks it without using the encryption key and encryption algorithm, they will still not be able to read its contents.
The information will look like a bunch of random numbers.
Most security systems rely on a secure key exchange method to transfer the encryption key to the right place.
However, the rapid development of computing power is jeopardizing a number of modern key exchange methods.
Consider one of the most widely used systems today - RSA.
When it was invented in 1977, it was estimated that it would take 40 quadrillion years to crack a 426-bit RSA key.
In 1994, just 17 years later, the code was cracked.
As computers got more powerful, we had to use more complex codes.
Today we usually use 2,048 or 4,096 bits.
As you can see, code creators and hackers are engaged in an ongoing battle trying to outsmart each other.
And when quantum computers arrive in the next 10-15 years, they will be able to break even faster the complex mathematics that underlies many modern encryption systems.
The quantum computer is likely to transform our current rugged fortress into a simple house of cards.
We must find a way to protect our fortress.
In recent years, there has been an increasing amount of research into the use of quantum effects to enhance crypto security.
Some interesting discoveries have been made.
Remember the three main elements of encryption: high quality keys, secure key exchange, and a sophisticated algorithm?
Advances in science and technology are jeopardizing two of these three elements.
First, the keys themselves.
Random numbers are the fundamental building blocks of encryption keys.
But today they are not entirely random.
Today we create encryption keys from sequences of random numbers generated from software, so-called pseudo-random numbers.
In the numbers generated by a program or a mathematical formula, one way or another, there is a certain pattern.
The less random the numbers - in scientific terminology: the less entropy they contain - the easier it is to predict them.
Several casinos have recently fallen victim to an ingenious attack.
The combinations at the output of the slot machines were recorded for some time, after which they were analyzed.
This allowed cybercriminals to redesign the pseudo-random number generator that drives the reels.
This, in turn, made it possible to predict the spins of the reels with high accuracy and get a big win.
Encryption keys can be subject to similar risks.
A truly random number generator is required for secure encryption.
For many years, scientists have been looking for the possibility of creating such a generator.
But most of the attempts today are either not random enough, not fast enough, or difficult to repeat.
But the quantum world is based on chance.
Therefore, it makes sense to take advantage of this fact.
Devices that can measure quantum effects can also generate an endless stream of random numbers at high speed,
which will stop all these potential casino criminals.
Some of the best universities and companies around the world are creating truly random number generators.
The first quantum generator I built was one meter by two meters and fit on an optical table.
Later we were able to shrink it down to the size of a server box.
Today it is about the size of a PCI card plugged into a standard computer.
It is the world's fastest truly random number generator.
Its performance is one billion random numbers per second.
Today it is used to strengthen the security system by cloud providers, banks, government agencies around the world.
(Applause) But even with such a generator, the second big problem remains unresolved: the threat to secure key exchange.
Modern key exchange methods are not compatible with a quantum computer.
The quantum solution to this problem is called "quantum key distribution" or QKD, which is based on a fundamental, paradoxical characteristic of quantum mechanics.
A quantum particle changes depending on its observation.
Let me give you an example of how it works.
Let's go back to exchanging the lock codes with James Bond.
Only this time, instead of calling James with the code, we'll use quantum effects on the laser to create the code and send it to James over a regular optical fiber.
We believe that Dr. No will try to hack access to data exchange.
Luckily, his attempts to trap the quantum keys along the way will leave fingerprints that James and you can find.
This will eliminate intercepted keys.
And the remaining keys can be used for enhanced data protection.
Since such security is based on fundamental laws of physics, a quantum computer or even any supercomputer of the future cannot break it.
My team and I are working with leading universities as well as the defense sector to develop this promising technology into the next generation of security.
The Internet of Things heralds an era of 25–30 billion devices projected to arrive by 2020.
Trust in the systems that support these devices is vital to the proper functioning of our society in the world of the Internet of Things.
I bet quantum technology can provide this trust, allowing us to take full advantage of the amazing innovations that will enrich our lives.
Thank you.
(Applause)
