Today I would like to show you how we will do different things in the future.
I believe that soon our buildings and machines will self-assemble, reproduce and repair themselves.
So I'm going to show you what I consider to be the current stage of industrial development, and then compare that to some natural systems.
So, at the current stage of industrial development, we have skyscrapers - 2.5 years, from 500,000 to a million parts, quite complex, new amazing technologies in steel, concrete and glass.
We have amazing machines that can take us into space - 5 years, 2.5 million parts.
But on the other hand, if we look at natural systems, we see proteins of two million species that can assemble in 10,000 nanoseconds, or a DNA strand with three billion base pairs that we can copy in about an hour.
So, natural systems, for all their complexity, are extremely efficient, much more efficient than anything we can build, much more complex than anything we can build.
They are much more energy efficient.
They are almost never wrong.
And they can regenerate themselves over a long life.
So there is something very interesting about natural systems.
And if we can bring that to our man-made environment, our way of creating things will have tremendous potential.
And I think the key is self-assembly.
So, if we want to use self-assembly in our physical environment, I think there are four key factors to consider.
First, we need to decipher the complexity of what we want to build - our buildings and cars.
And you need to decompose them into a simple sequence - the basic DNA of construction processes.
Then we need programmable parts that can understand this sequence and use it to fold or rebuild.
We will need some amount of energy that will allow all this to be activated, will make the parts able to assemble according to the program.
And we need some kind of back-up bug fixing system to ensure the successful construction of what we want.
I'm going to show you a few projects that my AmyTe colleagues and I are working on to achieve this self-assembled future.
The first two are MacroBot and DeciBot.
These are projects - large-scale reconfigurable robots - 2.5 and 3.5 meter squirrels.
They have built-in mechanical electrical devices, sensors.
You paint what you need to curl up into, in a sequence of angles - minus 120, minus 120, 0, 0, 120, minus 120 - something like that; a sequence of corners or turns, and you send that sequence down the cord.
Each block receives its own message - minus 120. It turns through this angle, checks if everything is correct and sends the information to its neighbor.
And these are brilliant scientists, engineers, designers who worked on this project.
And I think this actually brings up the question: are other scales possible here?
I mean, thousands of dollars, many man-hours to make this 2.5 meter robot.
Can we actually scale up? Can we really build robotics into every part?
The next project addresses this issue, considers the passive nature, or tries to get modification programmability passively.
But he goes one step further and tries to get the real computation.
At its core, it has the most fundamental building block of computation, the logic element of a digital integrated circuit directly in every part.
This is the NAND element.
You have one tetrahedron - the element that will do all the calculations, and two tetrahedrons for the input.
One for user input is the way you lay the bricks.
Another for information from a previous brick laid.
And then it outputs information in three-dimensional space.
So this means that the user can start moving the bricks in the desired direction.
His calculations are based on what was done earlier and on what you told him to do.
And now he begins to move in three-dimensional space - up or down.
On the left side, [1,1] input equals 0 on output, move down.
On the right side, [0,0] input is 1 output, which means upward movement.
And what's really important is that our structures now contain blueprints for what we want to build.
They contain all the information about what was built.
So this means that we have got some form of self-reproduction.
In this case, I call it self-directed reproduction because the structures contain clear blueprints.
If errors appear, you can replace the part.
All local information is saved so you know how to fix it.
So you can have something that moves and reads information and can transfer it from one part to another.
It is built directly inside, without external control.
The last project I'll show you is called Offset Chains, and this is perhaps the most exciting example of what we have of passive self-assembling systems right now.
It combines reconfiguration and programmability to create a completely passive system.
At the core we have a chain of elements.
All elements are completely identical and offset.
Thus, each chain or each element wants to turn right or left.
And when you build a chain, you are essentially programming it.
You tell each block where it should turn: right or left.
So when you shake the chain, it folds into the configuration you programmed - in this case, into a spiral, or in this case, two cubes next to each other.
So in general you can program any 3D shape - or 1D, 2D - of these completely passive circuits.
So what does this tell us about the future?
I think this tells us that there are new possibilities for self-assembly, replication, repair in our physical structures, buildings, machines.
New programming is possible in these parts.
And from here, you have new possibilities in computing.
We will have spatial computers.
Imagine that our buildings, bridges, cars, all our bricks could do calculations.
This is an amazing parallel and distributed subtraction power, new design possibilities.
This is incredible potential.
I think that the projects that I have shown you are only a small step towards the future, if we introduce these new technologies, towards a new self-assembling future.
Thank you.
