It is believed that only sighted people can drive a car.
Until recently, it was believed that safe and independent driving was an impossible task for the blind.
Hello, I am Denis Hong and we give the blind freedom and independence by developing cars for the visually impaired.
Before I talk about this vehicle for the blind, I will briefly talk about another project I was working on called the DARPA Urban Challenge.
The project was to create a self-driving robot car.
The driver presses "start", and without his participation, the car reaches its destination.
In 2007, our team won half a million dollars, finishing third in this competition.
Around the same time, the National Federation of the Blind, or NSF, challenged a research committee to develop a vehicle that could be independently and safely driven by a blind person.
We decided to try our hand because we thought: “Hey, what's so hard about that?
We already have an autonomous car.
We put a blind man in it - and the business is over, right? "
(Laughter) But we were deeply mistaken.
The NSF wanted to get not just a car that would transport the blind, but a car that a blind person could drive independently.
Therefore, we had to reject everything and start from scratch.
So, to test this crazy idea, we developed a small prototype of a buggy car to test the feasibility of the project.
And in the summer of 2009, we invited blind youth from all over the country and gave them the opportunity to test this car.
It was an amazing experience.
But the catch is that this car was designed to be driven in a tightly controlled environment, namely a flat, enclosed parking lot, where even lanes are delimited by red signal cones.
With this success, we decided to take the next big step and develop a real car that could be driven on real roads.
So how does it work?
Well, this is a rather complex system, but let me clarify, perhaps even simplify it.
So, it includes three components.
These are tactile perception, computation and non-visual interfaces.
Since the driver cannot see anything, the system must perceive the environment and collect information for the driver.
For this, the original parameter meter is used.
It measures acceleration, angular acceleration, like a person's inner ear.
This information is then transmitted to the GPS device to estimate the vehicle's location.
Two cameras are used to detect lane on the road
and three laser rangefinders.
Lasers scan the area around the car to detect various objects: an approaching oncoming or overtaking car, any obstacles encountered on the road or around the car.
Then all this huge amount of information is fed into the computer, and the computer goes through two stages.
First of all, this is the processing of this information to get an idea of the space: determining the lanes on the road, identifying obstacles, and then bringing this information to the driver.
The system is also smart enough to figure out the safest way to drive.
So, we can also give advice on how to operate the machine.
But the problem is how to get this information and instructions to a blind person who does not have the quick and accurate response needed to drive?
For this purpose, we have developed a number of interface technologies for the blind:
3D ping sound system, vibrating vest, steering wheel with beeps, special prosthetic leg, and even shoes that put pressure on the leg.
But today we will only talk about three kinds of these special interfaces.
The first interface is called DriveGrip.
This is a pair of gloves with motorized knuckles, instructing the driver how to steer: direction and steering angle.
Another device is the SpeedStrip.
It is originally a massage chair.
It was dismantled and the vibrating elements were rearranged in it. Vibration is used to provide speed information to the driver and to guide the use of the accelerator and brake pedals.
So, here you can see how the computer perceives the space around the car. And since vibration cannot be seen, red LEDs are installed on the driver to demonstrate the process.
This is sensory data, it is transmitted to devices by means of a computer.
DriveGrip and SpeedStrip are very efficient.
But the problem is that these are educational prompting devices.
They don't actually give freedom of control, do they?
The on-board computer gives the driver commands: "left", "right", "speed up", "stop".
We call him the "annoying backseat passenger".
Therefore, we are moving away from educational prompting devices and focusing our attention on informing devices.
AirPix is a great example of such an interface.
This is a kind of monitor for the blind.
A small panel with many openings through which compressed air exits, thereby creating images.
A blind person can bring a palm to this panel and "see" traffic lanes and obstacles on the roadway.
Also, the driver can change the frequency with which the air comes out and, possibly, the air temperature.
Those. it is an interface for displaying multidimensional data.
So, here you see the left and right cameras of the car, and how the computer processes and sends this information to the AirPix panel.
Here we demonstrate a simulator where a blind person drives a car using AirPix.
This simulator has proven to be very useful for training blind drivers as well as for quickly testing ideas for using different kinds of special interfaces.
This is, in a nutshell, how this system works.
After all, this is a prototype of a car for the blind. And he will not be released onto the roadway until they are convinced of his absolute safety.
And I sincerely believe that this is very likely.
Still, will society accept such a radical idea?
How much will the auto insurance rules change?
Under what conditions will a driver's license be issued?
Beyond the technological challenges, there are so many pitfalls that must be overcome before this becomes a reality.
Of course, the main goal of this project is to develop a vehicle for the blind.
However, it is possible that the spin-off technologies developed during this project will prove to be an invaluable contribution to our lives.
Our sensors work regardless of the time of day, fog and rain.
We can use these technologies together with new custom interfaces to improve vehicle safety for the sighted.
Or for the blind. Find their use in everyday household appliances, in educational institutions, in offices.
Just imagine: a teacher in a class is writing on a blackboard and a blind student can see and read what is written using these special interfaces.
It's priceless.
Therefore, what I have shown you today is just the beginning.
Many thanks.
(Applause)
